import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Function to plot class distribution
def plot_class_distribution(dataset):
    class_names = dataset.class_names
    class_counts = [0] * len(class_names)
    for images, labels in dataset:
        for label in labels:
            class_counts[label.numpy()] += 1
    plt.bar(class_names, class_counts)
    plt.xlabel('Class')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.title('Class Distribution')
    plt.show()

# Plot class distribution for train_dataset
plot_class_distribution(train_dataset)
  • This plot shows the two class "Dog" and "Cat" distribution which is similar for both classes(1000), as we load the dataset.

3. Train two networks¶

i. Neural Network with Custom Layers¶

In [ ]:
# Define the model
inputs = layers.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(inputs)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)

# Create the model
model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)

In this custom model:

  • The input layer receives data with a shape of (180, 180, 3), where 180x180 represents the height and width of the input image, and 3 represents the number of channels (RGB).
  • The rescaling layer scales the input data by dividing each pixel value by 255 to ensure it falls in the range [0, 1].
  • The convolutional layer-1 applies 64 filters of size 3x3 to the input data, resulting in an output tensor with a shape of (178, 178, 64).
  • Here, Total trainable parameter = (Size of Filter * Size of Filter * Number of Input Channels + bias) * Number of Filters

Total Trainable Parameters = (3 * 3 * 3 + 1) * 64 = (27 + 1) * 64 = 1792

  • The max pooling layer reduces the spatial dimensions of the input tensor by a factor of 2 along both the height and width dimensions, resulting in an output tensor with a shape of (89, 89, 64).
  • The same layers such as conv2d and max_pooling are added 3 more times with different parameters.
  • After the all layers there are total 981,633 parameters and all are trainable

Plot the training and validation loss and accuracy for Custom Model¶

In [ ]:
accuracy = history.history["accuracy"]
val_accuracy = history.history["val_accuracy"]
loss = history.history["loss"]
val_loss = history.history["val_loss"]
epochs = range(1, len(accuracy) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, accuracy, "bo", label="Training accuracy")
plt.plot(epochs, val_accuracy, "b", label="Validation accuracy")
plt.title("Training and validation accuracy")
plt.legend()
plt.figure()
plt.plot(epochs, loss, "bo", label="Training loss")
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, "b", label="Validation loss")
plt.title("Training and validation loss")
plt.legend()
Out[ ]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x27d01c3b290>

  • When we look at the training loss, it decreases consistently with each training iteration until it reaches its minimum value. However, when we examine the validation loss, which represents how well our model performs on unseen data, it started increased after some epoch.

  • Initially, the validation loss decreases steadily until around epoch 6. After that, it suddenly increases before dropping again at around a validation loss value of 0.5947 at epoch 9. The lowest validation loss occurs at epoch 9. However, after that point, the validation loss begins to rise again. This indicates that our model is starting to overfit the data - it's getting really good at memorizing the training examples, but it's not getting better at generalizing to new, unseen examples.

  • In conclusion, for our first model, the best weights are those obtained at epoch 9 because they correspond to the lowest validation loss.

VGG16 model:

  • There are total 16 layers in this Visual Geometry Group 16 (VGG16) model there are total 16 layers, which include input_2, conv2d, max_pooling2d these layers with different filters and combinations.
  • This model is already pre-trained on imagenet dataset.
  • The input layer receives data with a shape of (180, 180, 3), where 180x180 represents the height and width of the input image, and 3 represents the number of channels (RGB).
  • The convolutional layer-1 applies 64 filters of size 3x3 to the input data, resulting in an output tensor with a shape of (180, 180, 64).
  • Here, Total trainable parameter = (Size of Filter * Size of Filter * Number of Input Channels + bias) * Number of Filters

Total Trainable Parameters = (3 * 3 * 3 + 1) * 64 = (27 + 1) * 64 = 1792

  • The max pooling layer reduces the spatial dimensions of the input tensor by a factor of 2 along both the height and width dimensions, resulting in an output tensor with a shape of (90, 90, 64).
  • The same layers such as conv2d and max_pooling are added 13 and 5 times respectively with different parameters.
  • After the all layers there are total 14,714,688 parameters and all are trainable

Here we define a new dense neural networks, of only two trainable layers.

In [ ]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
x = keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input(inputs)
x = conv_base(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
x = layers.Dense(256)(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
model_vgg = keras.Model(inputs,outputs)

Freezing all layers until the fourth from the last

for layer in conv_base.layers[:-4]:
    layer.trainable=False

acc = history2.history["accuracy"]

loss = history2.history["loss"]
val_loss = history2.history["val_loss"]

plt.title("Training and validation loss")
plt.legend()
plt.show()
  1. From the above graph of validation & training accuracy, the training accuracy keeps improving after every epoch but the validation accuracy plateaus at value 0.97 from around 11 epoch, this is the indication of overfitting.
  2. From the above graph of validation & training accuracy, the training loss is keep reducing to nearly 0 value but, the validation loss make lowest validation loss = 0.2862 at epoch = 11 and then after shows slight increase after every epoch. So, this is also the indication of overfitting.

Confusion Matrix:
[[1000    0]
 [1000    0]]

The confusion matrix represent:

  1. True Positives (TP): The number of instances correctly predicted as class 0 (cat) is 1000.
  2. False Negatives (FN): The number of instances incorrectly predicted as class 1 (dog) when they are actually class 0 (cat) is 0.
  3. False Positives (FP): The number of instances incorrectly predicted as class 0 (cat) when they are actually class 1 (dog) is 1000.
  4. True Negatives (TN): The number of instances correctly predicted as class 1 (dog) is 0.

iii. Precision, Recall and F1-Score¶

In [ ]:
# Classification report

print("\n Classification Report:")
print(class_report)

 Classification Report:
              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.50      1.00      0.67      1000
           1       1.00      0.00      0.00      1000

    accuracy                           0.50      2000
   macro avg       0.75      0.50      0.33      2000
weighted avg       0.75      0.50      0.33      2000
  • Precision: Precision is a measure of the accuracy of the positive predictions. In this report:
  1. For class 0, the precision is 0.50, indicating that when the model predicts an instance as class 0, it is correct 50% of the time.
  2. For class 1, the precision is 1.00, implying that when the model predicts an instance as class 1, it is correct 100% of the time.
  • Recall: Recall is a measure of the completeness of the positive predictions. In this report:
  1. For class 0, the recall is 1.00, indicating that the model correctly identifies all instances of class 0.
  2. For class 1, the recall is 0.00, suggesting that the model fails to identify any instances of class 1.
  • F1-score: The F1-score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall, providing a balance between the two metrics. In this report:
  1. For class 0, the F1-score is 0.67, representing a balance between precision and recall for class 0.
  2. For class 1, the F1-score is 0.00, indicating poor performance in terms of precision and recall for class 1.

iv. Precision Recall Curve¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Calculate precision and recall values
precision, recall, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(true_labels, predictions)

# Define the threshold
threshold = 0.5  # Set your desired threshold value

# Plot precision-recall curve
plt.plot(recall, precision, 'b--', label='Precision-Recall Curve', linewidth=2)

# Plot threshold line
plt.vlines(threshold, 0, 1.0, 'k', 'dotted', label='Threshold')

# Mark the point corresponding to the threshold
idx = (thresholds >= threshold).argmax()
plt.plot(recall[idx], precision[idx], 'bo')

# Set plot properties
plt.xlabel('Recall')
plt.ylabel('Precision')
plt.title('Precision-Recall Curve')
plt.legend(loc='lower left')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
  • Looking at the precision-recall plot, it seems the model does a good job at being precise when it predicts class 1 (dog), but it misses quite a few actual class 1 instances, showing a bit of a struggle with recall. This suggests that while it's accurate in labeling things as class 1, it's not catching all the actual class 1 instances, which might need some tweaking to improve overall performance.

5. Conclusion¶

1. Custom Model

  • The test accuracy for above custom model is 70.5% on the test set.
  • Initially, the validation loss decreases steadily until around epoch 6. After that, it suddenly increases before dropping again at around a validation loss value of 0.5947 at epoch 9. for our custom model, the best weights are those obtained at epoch 9 because they correspond to the lowest validation loss.

2. VGG16 Model

  • In training the VGG16 model we first load the pre trained VGG16 model on Imagenet data and then we freeze the all layers exceptr the last 4 layers. Then, we trained the model on the trainable parameters.
  • The accuracy for above VGG16 model is 96.6% on the test set.
  1. From the above graph of validation & training accuracy, the training accuracy keeps improving after every epoch but the validation accuracy plateaus at value 0.97 from around 11 epoch, this is the indication of overfitting.
  2. From the above graph of validation & training accuracy, the training loss is keep reducing to nearly 0 value but, the validation loss make lowest validation loss = 0.2862 at epoch = 11 and then after shows slight increase after every epoch. So, this is also the indication of overfitting.
